<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate take-home pay from my hourly wage?", answer: "To calculate take-home pay, first determine your gross pay by multiplying your hourly rate by hours worked. Then subtract federal income tax (based on annual equivalent income and tax brackets), state income tax, Social Security (6.2%), and Medicare (1.45%). For example, at $20/hour working 40 hours/week, your gross annual equivalent is about $41,600, and your net pay after all deductions is typically 70-80% of gross." },
  { question: "How is overtime pay calculated?", answer: "Under federal law (FLSA), overtime is paid at 1.5 times your regular hourly rate for hours worked beyond 40 in a workweek. Some states have additional rules, like daily overtime after 8 hours (California). For example, if your regular rate is $20/hour, overtime pays $30/hour. Overtime pay is subject to the same tax withholdings as regular pay." },
  { question: "What is the difference between part-time and full-time for tax purposes?", answer: "For federal tax purposes, there is no legal distinction between part-time and full-time workers — both are taxed the same way based on total annual income. However, the ACA defines full-time as 30+ hours per week for employer health insurance requirements. Part-time workers earning less may fall into lower tax brackets, resulting in a lower effective tax rate on each paycheck." },
  { question: "How do I convert my hourly wage to annual salary?", answer: "Multiply your hourly rate by the number of hours you work per week, then multiply by 52 weeks. For a standard 40-hour week: $15/hour = $31,200/year, $20/hour = $41,600/year, $25/hour = $52,000/year, $30/hour = $62,400/year. If you work fewer hours or take unpaid time off, adjust the weeks accordingly." },
  { question: "Do I still pay Social Security and Medicare on hourly wages?", answer: "Yes, all hourly wages are subject to FICA taxes: 6.2% for Social Security (up to the wage base of $168,600 in 2024) and 1.45% for Medicare (on all wages, plus 0.9% additional Medicare tax on wages over $200,000). Your employer matches these amounts, paying an equal 7.65% on your behalf." }
]) %>

