    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Hourly Paycheck Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Our free hourly paycheck calculator helps you estimate your take-home pay based on an hourly wage. To use it, convert your hourly rate to an annual salary by multiplying your hourly rate by your weekly hours, then by 52 weeks. For example, $20 per hour at 40 hours per week equals $41,600 annually. Enter this amount, select your state tax level and pay frequency (weekly is most common for hourly workers), and the calculator will break down your per-paycheck net pay, annual totals, and all deductions.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding your real take-home pay is essential for budgeting, especially for hourly workers whose income can vary with hours worked. This calculator shows exactly how much of each paycheck goes to federal tax, state tax, Social Security, and Medicare, so you can plan your finances accurately whether you work full-time, part-time, or pick up overtime hours.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Calculating Hourly Pay to Annual Salary</h2>
      <p>
        The standard conversion formula is simple: hourly rate multiplied by hours per week multiplied by 52 weeks per year. A $15 per hour wage at 40 hours per week equals $31,200 annually. At $20 per hour, that becomes $41,600. At $25 per hour, $52,000. At $30 per hour, $62,400. If you work fewer than 40 hours or take unpaid time off, reduce the number of weeks accordingly. For part-time workers at 20 hours per week, the annual equivalent is halved.
      </p>

      <h3>Understanding Overtime Pay</h3>
      <p>
        Under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), non-exempt hourly employees must receive overtime pay at 1.5 times their regular rate for all hours worked beyond 40 in a workweek. Some states have stricter rules, such as California, which requires overtime after 8 hours in a single day. Overtime pay is taxed the same way as regular wages — it does not push you into a higher bracket on that specific pay, but it does increase your total annual income, which may affect your overall tax liability.
      </p>

      <h3>Part-Time vs. Full-Time: Tax Implications</h3>
      <p>
        Federal tax law does not distinguish between part-time and full-time employment. Both are taxed identically based on total annual earnings. However, part-time workers earning less may benefit from lower tax brackets and a higher percentage of their standard deduction relative to income. Part-time workers who earn less than $14,600 (the 2024 standard deduction for single filers) may owe no federal income tax at all, though FICA taxes still apply to every dollar earned.
      </p>

      <h2>Hourly Rate to Annual Net Pay Reference</h2>
      <p>
        This reference table converts common US hourly rates to annual gross pay (at 40 hours/week × 52 weeks) and approximate net take-home for a single filer claiming the standard deduction, medium state tax (~5%), and no pre-tax deductions. Use your state's actual rate for a tighter estimate; the calculator above handles the math precisely when you enter your own inputs.
      </p>
